<subSubSection pageId="42" pageNumber="43" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Found inall the zoogeographical regions. In the Afrotropical region this genus is known from Ethiopia, Kenya, Republic of South Africa, Tanzania and Socotra Island (Yemen) (Fig. 360).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="42" pageNumber="43" type="ecology">
<paragraph pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="42" pageNumber="43">
Known host plants for this genus fall in the plant families Cruciferae (= Brassicaeae), 
<taxonomicName genus="Solanaceae" lsidName="Solanaceae" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" rank="genus">Solanaceae</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="Poaceae" lsidName="Poaceae" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" rank="genus">Poaceae</taxonomicName>
(also known as 
<taxonomicName genus="Gramineae" lsidName="Gramineae" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" rank="genus">Gramineae</taxonomicName>
) (cf. 
<bibRefCitation author="Jolivet, P" journalOrPublisher="An essay about the relationships between the leaf-beetles and their food-plants. Backhuys Publishers, Leiden" pageId="52" pageNumber="53" title="Host-plants of Chrysomelidae of the World." year="1995">Jolivet and Hawkeswood 1995</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
